The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Thursday, July 29, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Bhubaneswar, July 28: Panic gripped the passengers of the Howrah-bound Puri Express last evening after the engine caught fire  sparked by a short-circuit  shortly after leaving Puri. No one was injured. 				 																																	By the time the train reached the next station, the engine was burning and the driver stopped. Half-an-hour later, fire-fighters reached, brought the fire under control and separated the engine from the rake. The authorities later attached another one from nearby Purushottampur station and the train left for Howrah. 				 																																	Barasat: Unable to tolerate his mothers illicit relationship with a local timber merchant, 22-year-old Amit Ghosh, a student of Barasat Government College, committed suicide on Tuesday night. Amit found his mother and her paramour in a compromising position when he returned home. He rushed to his bedroom and hung himself from the ceiling fan. Amits mother was arrested on a complaint by his father. 				 																																	Calcutta: Seven persons were injured when SFI and Trinamul Congress Chhatra Parishad supporters clashed at Behala College over distribution of admission forms. Five persons, including three SFI members, have been arrested. 				 																																	Howrah: The Left Front formed the Uluberia municipal board in Howrah, more than a month after the civic body elections. There was tie in the polls between the Front on the one hand and the Trinamul Congress, Congress and the BJP on the other. Both sides kept claiming they would emerge with a majority. When they failed, a toss was held. Batakrishna Das of CPM was appointed the chairman.
